source: crates/webpkit-cli/tests/snapshot.rs
expression: "dump(\"webp\", \"--help\")"
---
$ webp --help
Command-line tools for the webpkit WebP codec: libwebp-style cwebp (lossy by default, -lossless for VP8L) / dwebp and the webp brand tool.

Usage: webp [OPTIONS] [INPUTS]...
       webp <COMMAND>

Commands:
  decode       Decode a WebP file to PNG (default), PPM/PAM, or raw pixels
  encode       Encode an image (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM/raw) into a WebP file
  convert      Batch-convert many images (or directories) to WebP, in parallel
  animate      Assemble still images into an animated WebP (surpasses img2webp/gif2webp)
  mux          Edit an animated WebP without re-encoding frames (webpmux-parity muxing)
  info         Print a summary of a WebP file (size, alpha, metadata, animation)
  meta         Read, set, or strip a WebP file's metadata (ICC/Exif/XMP), without re-encoding the image
  diff         Compare two images: report PSNR and the largest per-channel difference
  doctor       Diagnose the environment: PATH drop-in shadows, config, terminal, threads
  config       Show resolved settings and where each came from (args, env, file, default)
  explain      Explain an exit code: what a failing run's status number means
  completions  Print a shell completion script
  man          Print a man page in roff, for `man -l -` or a package's man directory
  help         Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)

Arguments:
  [INPUTS]...
          Images or directories. A WebP is decoded to PNG; anything else is encoded

Options:
  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never [default: auto, or from env/config].
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored; an explicit `--color` outranks them and `WEBP_COLOR`/`webp.toml`. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --dry-run
          Report what would be written, without encoding or writing anything

  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output file, or a directory for many inputs; default: beside each input

  -q, --quality <QUALITY>
          Lossy quality 0-100 (higher = larger, closer to source); selects lossy

      --lossless
          Force lossless (VP8L) encoding

      --lossy
          Force lossy (VP8) encoding

      --near-lossless <N>
          Near-lossless preprocessing 0-100 (lower = stronger; implies lossless)

  -m, --method <METHOD>
          Encoder effort [default: auto, or from env/config]

          Possible values:
          - auto: Adapt the search depth to the image's content and size (the default)
          - fast: Fastest: the shallowest fixed search
          - best: Smallest: the deepest fixed search

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Metadata to embed: all,none,icc,exif,xmp (default: all)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

      --crop <X,Y,W,H>
          Crop before encoding: `x,y,width,height` in pixels (applied before --resize)

      --resize <WxH>
          Resize before encoding: `WxH` (use 0 on one axis to keep aspect)

  -r, --recursive
          Recurse into subdirectories

      --force
          Overwrite an existing derived output

      --no-clobber
          Skip an existing derived output instead of failing (still exits 0)

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

  -V, --version
          Print version

$ webp decode --help
Decode a WebP file to PNG (default), PPM/PAM, or raw pixels

Usage: webp decode [OPTIONS] --output <OUTPUT> [INPUT]

Arguments:
  [INPUT]
          Input `.webp` file; `-` (the default) reads stdin
          
          [default: -]

Options:
  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output path; `-` writes stdout

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --format <FORMAT>
          Output format; defaults to the `-o` extension, else PNG

          Possible values:
          - png:  PNG, RGBA8
          - ppm:  Netpbm binary PPM (`P6`, RGB; alpha dropped)
          - pam:  Netpbm binary PAM (`P7`, RGBA)
          - bmp:  BMP (RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - tiff: TIFF (RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - raw:  Raw row-major pixels in the requested `--layout`

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never [default: auto, or from env/config].
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored; an explicit `--color` outranks them and `WEBP_COLOR`/`webp.toml`. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.

      --layout <LAYOUT>
          Byte order for raw output only

          Possible values:
          - rgba8: `R, G, B, A`
          - argb8: `A, R, G, B`
          - bgra8: `B, G, R, A`
          
          [default: rgba8]

      --frames <FRAMES>
          For animations: which frames to emit

          Possible values:
          - first: Only the first composited frame (the default)
          - all:   Every composited frame, numbered `<stem>-000.<ext>`, ...

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --dry-run
          Report what would be written, without encoding or writing anything

      --frame <FRAME>
          For animations: emit only this 0-based frame

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Metadata to carry into the output: all,none,icc,exif,xmp (default: all)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp encode --help
Encode an image (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM/raw) into a WebP file

Usage: webp encode [OPTIONS] --output <OUTPUT> [INPUT]

Arguments:
  [INPUT]
          Input image (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM/raw); `-` (default) reads stdin
          
          [default: -]

Options:
  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output `.webp` file; `-` writes stdout

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --input-format <INPUT_FORMAT>
          Input format; defaults to the extension, else the magic bytes, else raw

          Possible values:
          - png:  PNG (any color type; normalized to RGBA8)
          - ppm:  Netpbm binary PPM (`P6`, RGB)
          - pam:  Netpbm binary PAM (`P7`, RGBA)
          - jpeg: JPEG (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - gif:  GIF (first frame as a still; whole-file animation is a separate path)
          - tiff: TIFF (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - bmp:  BMP (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - raw:  Raw row-major pixels; requires `--width`/`--height`/`--layout`

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never [default: auto, or from env/config].
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored; an explicit `--color` outranks them and `WEBP_COLOR`/`webp.toml`. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.

      --width <WIDTH>
          Raw-input width in pixels (required for raw input)

      --height <HEIGHT>
          Raw-input height in pixels (required for raw input)

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --dry-run
          Report what would be written, without encoding or writing anything

      --layout <LAYOUT>
          Byte order for raw input only

          Possible values:
          - rgba8: `R, G, B, A`
          - argb8: `A, R, G, B`
          - bgra8: `B, G, R, A`
          
          [default: rgba8]

  -m, --method <METHOD>
          Encoder effort [default: auto, or from env/config]

          Possible values:
          - auto: Adapt the search depth to the image's content and size (the default)
          - fast: Fastest: the shallowest fixed search
          - best: Smallest: the deepest fixed search

      --lossless
          Force lossless (VP8L). The default is source-derived: JPEG → lossy, else lossless

      --lossy
          Encode lossily (VP8) instead of losslessly (VP8L)

  -q, --quality <QUALITY>
          Lossy quality 0-100 (higher = larger, closer to source); selects --lossy

      --near-lossless <N>
          Near-lossless preprocessing 0-100 (lower = stronger; implies lossless)

      --crop <X,Y,W,H>
          Crop before encoding: `x,y,width,height` in pixels (applied before --resize)

      --resize <WxH>
          Resize before encoding: `WxH` (use 0 on one axis to keep aspect)

      --target-size <SIZE>
          Target output size, e.g. `200k` or `2M`, found by searching lossy quality.
          
          Lossy only: it bisects quality until the encoded file fits. With `-v`, the search is printed. Cannot combine with `--lossless`.

      --min-psnr <DB>
          Target reconstruction PSNR floor in dB (lossy only; pairs with --target-size)

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Metadata to embed: all,none,icc,exif,xmp (default: all — kinder than cwebp)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

      --optimize
          Inter-frame optimize a GIF animation: encode each frame as a minimal delta

      --mixed
          With --optimize: trial each frame lossy and lossless, keep the smaller (gif2webp -mixed)

      --min-size
          With --optimize: exhaustively search each frame's rect/blend/dispose/codec (gif2webp `-min_size`)

      --kmax <N>
          With --optimize: force a keyframe at least every N frames (gif2webp -kmax; 0 = only the first)

      --kmin <N>
          With --optimize: never place keyframes closer than N frames apart (gif2webp -kmin)

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp convert --help
Batch-convert many images (or directories) to WebP, in parallel

Usage: webp convert [OPTIONS] <INPUTS>...

Arguments:
  <INPUTS>...
          Input images and/or directories (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM)

Options:
  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output directory (created outputs are `<stem>.webp`); default: beside input

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

  -m, --method <METHOD>
          Encoder effort (ignored with --optimize) [default: auto, or from env/config]

          Possible values:
          - auto: Adapt the search depth to the image's content and size (the default)
          - fast: Fastest: the shallowest fixed search
          - best: Smallest: the deepest fixed search

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never [default: auto, or from env/config].
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored; an explicit `--color` outranks them and `WEBP_COLOR`/`webp.toml`. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.

      --lossless
          Force lossless (VP8L). The default is source-derived: JPEG → lossy, else lossless

      --lossy
          Encode lossily (VP8) instead of losslessly (VP8L)

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --dry-run
          Report what would be written, without encoding or writing anything

  -q, --quality <QUALITY>
          Lossy quality 0-100 (higher = larger, closer to source); selects --lossy

      --near-lossless <N>
          Near-lossless preprocessing 0-100 (lower = stronger; implies lossless)

      --optimize
          Try every lossless effort level and keep the smallest output

  -r, --recursive
          Recurse into subdirectories

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Metadata to embed: all,none,icc,exif,xmp (default: all)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

      --force
          Overwrite an existing output

      --no-clobber
          Skip an input whose `.webp` output exists (still exits 0)

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp animate --help
Assemble still images into an animated WebP (surpasses img2webp/gif2webp).

Each input (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM) is decoded and added as one frame. `--delay` sets the per-frame duration (one value for all, or a comma list), `--loop` the loop count, and `--lossy Q` switches from the lossless default. The canvas defaults to the largest frame, or set it with `--canvas WxH`.

Usage: webp animate [OPTIONS] --output <OUTPUT> <INPUTS>...

Arguments:
  <INPUTS>...
          Still images, one per frame, in display order (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM)

Options:
  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output `.webp` file; `-` writes stdout

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --delay <MS>
          Per-frame delay in ms: one value for every frame, or a comma list (`40,40,80`)
          
          [default: 100]

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never [default: auto, or from env/config].
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored; an explicit `--color` outranks them and `WEBP_COLOR`/`webp.toml`. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.

      --loop <N>
          Loop count; `0` (the default) loops forever
          
          [default: 0]

      --bgcolor <RRGGBBAA>
          Advisory background color as `RRGGBBAA` hex (e.g. `ffffffff`)

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --dispose <DISPOSE>
          Disposal method applied to every frame

          Possible values:
          - keep:       Leave the canvas as-is for the next frame (the default)
          - background: Clear the frame's rectangle to transparent before the next frame
          
          [default: keep]

      --dry-run
          Report what would be written, without encoding or writing anything

      --blend <BLEND>
          Blend method applied to every frame

          Possible values:
          - blend:     Alpha-blend the frame over the canvas (the default)
          - overwrite: Overwrite the frame's rectangle, ignoring what is underneath
          
          [default: blend]

      --lossy <Q>
          Encode frames lossily (VP8) at this quality 0-100; the default is lossless

      --canvas <WxH>
          Canvas size as `WxH`; defaults to the largest frame

  -m, --method <METHOD>
          Encoder effort [default: auto, or from env/config]

          Possible values:
          - auto: Adapt the search depth to the image's content and size (the default)
          - fast: Fastest: the shallowest fixed search
          - best: Smallest: the deepest fixed search

      --input-format <INPUT_FORMAT>
          Force the input format instead of sniffing each file

          Possible values:
          - png:  PNG (any color type; normalized to RGBA8)
          - ppm:  Netpbm binary PPM (`P6`, RGB)
          - pam:  Netpbm binary PAM (`P7`, RGBA)
          - jpeg: JPEG (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - gif:  GIF (first frame as a still; whole-file animation is a separate path)
          - tiff: TIFF (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - bmp:  BMP (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - raw:  Raw row-major pixels; requires `--width`/`--height`/`--layout`

      --optimize
          Inter-frame optimize: encode each frame as a minimal delta against the canvas.
          
          The optimizer derives each frame's rectangle, blend, and dispose itself so the result composites pixel-identically to the full-frame animation, only smaller; `--blend` and `--dispose` are therefore ignored under `--optimize`.

      --mixed
          With --optimize: trial each frame lossy and lossless, keep the smaller (gif2webp -mixed)

      --min-size
          With --optimize: exhaustively search each frame's rect/blend/dispose/codec (gif2webp `-min_size`)

      --kmax <N>
          With --optimize: force a keyframe at least every N frames (gif2webp -kmax; 0 = only the first)

      --kmin <N>
          With --optimize: never place keyframes closer than N frames apart (gif2webp -kmin)

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp mux --help
Edit an animated WebP without re-encoding frames (webpmux-parity muxing).

Extract a frame, edit the loop count / background, or insert / remove / replace frames — every untouched frame's encoded bytes pass through byte-for-byte, and the ICC/Exif/XMP metadata is preserved.

Usage: webp mux [OPTIONS] <COMMAND>

Commands:
  get-frame  Extract one frame as a standalone still WebP (bytes copied verbatim)
  set        Rewrite the loop count and/or background color
  remove     Remove one frame, rebuilding the frame list
  insert     Insert a still WebP as a new frame (its image bytes copied verbatim)
  replace    Replace one frame's image with a still WebP, keeping its placement/timing
  help       Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)

Options:
  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never [default: auto, or from env/config].
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored; an explicit `--color` outranks them and `WEBP_COLOR`/`webp.toml`. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --dry-run
          Report what would be written, without encoding or writing anything

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

