$ webp diff --help
Compare two images: report PSNR and the largest per-channel difference.

Both inputs are decoded to RGBA (a WebP, or any readable image), so a source and its WebP, or two WebP files, can be compared. With `--min-psnr`, exit 1 when the PSNR is below the threshold — the grep/diff convention, for CI gates.

Usage: webp diff [OPTIONS] <A> <B>

Arguments:
  <A>
          The first image (a WebP, or any readable format)

  <B>
          The second image, compared against the first (same dimensions required)

Options:
      --min-psnr <DB>
          Fail (exit 1) if the RGB PSNR is below this many decibels

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --json
          Print the comparison as JSON instead of text

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never [default: auto, or from env/config].
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored; an explicit `--color` outranks them and `WEBP_COLOR`/`webp.toml`. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --dry-run
          Report what would be written, without encoding or writing anything

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp doctor --help
Diagnose the environment: PATH drop-in shadows, config, terminal, threads.

Exits 0 even with warnings; 1 only on a real error (an invalid config file).

Usage: webp doctor [OPTIONS]

